{
  "answer": "**The maqta (the concluding couplet of the ghazal, featuring the poet's takhallus \"Zauq\") is the tenth and final sher:**\n\n**Original (Urdu):**  \nوہ دل کہ جس میں سوز_محبت نہ ہووے ذوقؔ  \nبہتر ہے سنگ اس سے کہ اس میں شرر تو ہے[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nWoh dil ke jiss mein soz-e-mohabbat na hove 'Zauq'  \nBehtar hai sang uss se ke uss mein sharar toh hai[^2]\n\n**Translation:**  \nO Zauq, a heart that has no fire of love  \nIs worse than stone, which has a fiery core, at least.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/16-ek-sadma-dard-e-dil-se-meri-jaan-par-toh-hai/original/#p-0786bf).\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 16 (transliteration).[^4]\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/16-ek-sadma-dard-e-dil-se-meri-jaan-par-toh-hai/translation/#p-df8cda).\n[^4]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 16.[^5]\n\nThe ghazal consists of 10 couplets, each a radif ending in \"*toh hai*\" (\"at least\"), emphasizing reluctant consolation amid suffering.[^6]\n\n[^5]: Note: Exact paragraph citation for transliteration unavailable due to variant mismatch; refers to the final couplet in the chapter body.\n[^6]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 16 (full chapter).",
